<F P=101> Romania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Reorganizes ROMPRES News Agency </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Reorganizes ROMPRES News Agency </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1506131494 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 1114 GMT 15 Jun 94 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1506131494 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest ROMPRES, 15/6/1994 -- The Government of 
Romania approved in its Tuesday, 14 June, meeting a resolution 
for the reorganization of the national news agency ROMPRES. The 
reorganization of ROMPRES is required by the need for a clearer 
definition of its objectives and for the improvement of its 
activities; for the need to provide it with the necessary 
juridical status and functional pattern in tune with the 
importance of a public institution of national interest. 
  The government resolution spells the importance of the role 
and duties the national news agency ROMPRES has in ensuring a 
prompt and objective conveyance of information to both the 
Romanian and foreign press, and its provisions pursue to 
stimulate the agency's participation in the information flow in 
Romania and to enhance its cooperation with the national and 
international press agencies. 
  The resolution defines the national news agency ROMPRES as a 
public institution of national interest, financed by the state 
budget and operating at the legal and financial standards valid 
for all budget-subsidized institutions. 
  ROMPRES carries out its attributions free from any 
ideological, political, or economic influences or partiality 
likely to impair the accuracy of the information it releases. 
  In order to adequately fulfill its attributions, ROMPRES is 
authorized to request press information from state institutions, 
ministries, and other bodies of the central and local public 
authorities. 
  ROMPRES staff are entitled, in the exerting of their duties, 
to legal protection, in similar conditions with any civil 
servant. The specialized staff engaged in activities specific 
for the press have the rights and duties as devolving upon them 
from the profession of journalist, and, as such, are entitled to 
the protection of the law. 
  The general director of the national news agency ROMPRES is 
appointed by the prime minister, his position being equivalent 
to that of a secretary of state. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

