<H3> <TI>   Negotiations With Serbian Krajina Canceled </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Negotiations With Serbian Krajina Canceled </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    RSK Foreign Minister Comments </H4>

<F P=102> LD1606183894 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1724 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1606183894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Knin, 16 Jun (TANJUG) -- The government of the 
republic of Serb Krajina [RSK] has done all it can over the past 
couple of days to continue the negotiating process with the 
Republic of Croatia on principles of equality and respect for 
the sovereignty and interests of the RSK, RSK Foreign Minister 
Milan Babic said in Knin today. 
  We did not make the continuation of the talks conditional on 
anything, but Croatia yesterday began its blockade of the 
negotiating process in a bizarre way--with a banal demand to 
allow five Croatian reporters to attend and cover the Plitvice 
talks. By substituting form for substance, they set this as the 
condition for the resumption of the talks. They managed to 
block the negotiations, as they had decided beforehand. They 
even proposed a final text of the agreement they wished us to 
sign in Plitvice, the ISKRA news agency quoted the Krajina 
foreign minister as saying. 
  We expect international factors to do all in their power so 
the peace process with Croatia could resume with the aim of 
achieving a lasting peace, which is in the interest of the Serb 
people and other members of the international community, Babic 
said while commenting on the postponement of the talks with 
Croatia. 

</TEXT>

