<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Two Ethnic Hungarian Parties Coalesce </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Two Ethnic Hungarian Parties Coalesce </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1606131894 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
1000 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1606131894 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Hungarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A coalition agreement on future cooperation was 
reached on 15 June between the Hungarian Christian Democratic 
Movement in Slovakia and Coexistence. Ildiko Nagy reports from 
Bratislava on the details: 
  [Begin Nagy recording] It lays down close political 
cooperation, the setting up of joint bodies, a dual election 
coalition, and further expansion with a third partner. The two 
sides also agreed that they would begin discussions soon with 
the Hungarian Civic Party on expanding the dual coalition into a 
triple one. 
  In answer to a question from Hungarian radio's correspondent 
[Nagy], Bela Bugar, chairman of the Hungarian Christian 
Democratic Movement, said he was satisfied with the result 
because they managed to achieve what the movement's national 
executive asked the negotiating delegation to do: to try to form 
a triple coalition. The two partners have already agreed on the 
conditions for this; however, this will be made public only 
after the dual coalition agreement is signed next week. 
  The documents adopted at the 8 January 1994 Komarno rally 
constitute the basis of the agreement. If these are acceptable 
to the third party--that is, the Hungarian Civic Party--then, in 
the view of the Hungarian Christian Democratic Movement 
chairman, they will succeed in forming a triple election 
alliance. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

