<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Krajisnik: Maps `Far From Acceptable' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Krajisnik: Maps `Far From Acceptable' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1606172494 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1640 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1606172494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 16 Jun (TANJUG) -- Momcilo Krajisnik, the 
president of the People's Assembly of the Bosnian Serb Republic, 
told TANJUG today that the maps, under review by the Contact 
Group for the former Bosnia-Herzegovina, were far from 
acceptable for the Serbs. We have had a preliminary look at the 
maps, but we are expecting some improvements, that is, 
corrections. If that happens, it will be create favorable 
conditions for the restoration of peace in Bosnia, Krajisnik 
said. He particularly stressed that the maps, which have been 
circulated, were causing concern and fears among the Serb people 
that they could be imposed on the Serbs in their current form. 
  The maps considerably affect the vital interests of the Serb 
people and, in fact, they are destroying the achievements of our 
struggle for the homeland, which is impermissible. I do not 
want to pass any judgments on the maps. However, I am expecting 
reasonable proposals because we presented our objections and 
explained why we could not accept their proposals. We also 
invited the Muslims side to present their stances. 
  We are awaiting a response with great interest. Our reaction 
to the response will in any event be in line with the proposals 
adopted by the Serb Republic People's Assembly at the last two 
sessions, Krajisnik said in conclusion. 

</TEXT>

