<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Insists on Observing Serb-Held Areas </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army Insists on Observing Serb-Held Areas </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1606200194 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1700 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1606200194 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Colonel (Plafait), authorized representative of the 
UN Headquarters for Bosnia-Herzegovina, today presented 
Brigadier General Enver Hadzihasanovic, commander of the General 
Staff of the Supreme Command of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Army, 
with a proposal to deploy UN observers in charge of monitoring 
and reporting on the observation of the cease-fire agreed upon 
in Geneva on 8 June, the Bosnia-Herzegovina Army press center 
informs. The proposal of the UN Headquarters for 
Bosnia-Herzegovina is in accordance with the conclusions of the 
meeting of the commanders of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Army and the 
United Nations. It envisages the construction of 66 observation 
points in the southwest and northeast sectors. 
  The Serbian aggressor's side has not delivered its proposal 
to the UN Command for Bosnia-Herzegovina yet. The final version 
on the observation posts can, therefore, be expected at the next 
meeting. The General Staff of the Supreme Command of the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Army continues to insist on an improved 
number and place of deployed UN observers, especially in the 
Bihac and Gorazde regions. If the observation posts are not set 
up on the territories temporarily controlled by the Serbian 
aggressor's side, then we will not accept and allow observation 
posts to be constructed on the free territory of the Republic of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, is written in the statement by the Army 
Press Center. 
  The Bosnia-Herzegovina Army proposal on the number of 
liaison 
officers and line of administration and command has been 
accepted in its entirety by the UN Command for 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. The proposal facilitates efficient 
surveillance and reporting by the incumbent commands on the 
observation of the cease-fire. 

</TEXT>

