<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslim, Croatian Cease-Fire Violations Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Muslim, Croatian Cease-Fire Violations Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1606171794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1651 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1606171794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Zvornik, June 16 (TANJUG) -- Bosnian Moslem and 
Croat forces continued to violate the one-month ceasefire in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, Bosnian Serb military sources said Thursday 
[16 June]. Bosnian Moslem and Croat troops, whose political 
leaders three months ago signed a U.S.-mediated federation 
agreement, continued offensive action in numerous areas of the 
former Yugoslav republic. Around the town of Orasje in the 
Posavina region of northern Bosnia, joint units of Bosnian 
Croats and regular Croatian Army troops made sporadic artillery 
attacks on Serb positions. 
  Soldiers from the regular Croatian Army have been deployed 
in 
and around Orasje since the start of the Bosnian civil war in 
April 1992. The Bosnian Serb forces suffered no losses in the 
latest attack and did not return fire, Serb military sources in 
Brcko said early on Thursday. Bosnian Moslem forces opened 
mortar fire on Teslic, a town in northern Bosnia, wounding six 
civilians, including two children, Serb military sources said. 
  The Moslems also launched attacks in a wide region around 
the 
northern Bosnian town of Doboj and the Borci region between 
Kalinovik and Konjic in eastern Herzegovina. Heavy Moslem 
artillery attacks were also reported around Kladanj in eastern 
Bosnia. Bosnian Serb sources reported that Moslem units opened 
fire in the Sarajevo region, firing mainly into Sarajevo's Serb 
residential areas of Ilijas and Hadzici. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

