<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Spokesman: No Information on Banja Luka </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Spokesman: No Information on Banja Luka </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1606222394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2137 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1606222394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] New York, June 16 (TANJUG) -- The United Nations has 
no information about any "ethnic cleansing" being practiced in 
the Bosnian Serb town of Banja Luka, a U.N. spokesman said on 
Thursday [16 June]. The statement was prompted by a NEW YORK 
TIMES report from Sarajevo alleging that an "ethnic cleansing" 
campaign in Banja Luka in western Bosnia-Herzegovina has 
intensified and that more than 3,000 Moslems and Croats have 
fled the town under Serb pressure in the past two months. The 
U.N. secretary-general's spokesman Joe Sills said that a Moslem 
offensive had abated after having raged for weeks and that the 
truce signed by Bosnia's belligerents at Geneva on June 8 was 
holding in the main, except for fierce fighting around Bihac in 
the west between rival Moslem factions loyal to hardliner Alija 
Izetbegovic and his moderate opponent Fikret Abdic. 
  Abdic and his supporters rebelled against Izetbegovic's 
war-mongering policy and last autumn proclaimed their autonomous 
province of western Bosnia and signed peace accords with Bosnian 
Serbs and Croats. Sills said that Bosnian Serb forces had been 
holding a Nordic medical convoy near Rogatica, southeast of 
Sarajevo, for the past three days in violation of an agreement 
on free passage throughout Bosnian territory. Asked if it was 
true that the convoy had refused to submit to a routine check, 
Sills replied that, according to his information, the Serbs were 
asking for more than a routine check, which he said was giving 
rise to concern. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-31956 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu117_i_94009" </HT>


