<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   CSCE High Commissioners Meet in Prague </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    CSCE High Commissioners Meet in Prague </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1506161894 Prague CTK in English 1156 GMT 15 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1506161894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, June 15 (CTK) -- The situation in the 
Central and Eastern European countries and the future policy and 
meaning of the Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe 
(CSCE) was discussed at the three-day 27th meeting of CSCE High 
Commissioners which ended today. 
  The participants discussed the role of CSCE missions in the 
countries of the former Soviet Union, namely Nagorno-Karabakh, 
South Ossetia and Georgia and in ex-Yugoslavia, as well as the 
presence of Russian troops in the Baltic states, Piotr Switalski 
from the Secretariat of the acting chairman of the CSCE High 
Commission told journalists. The commissioners also discussed 
the Budapest meeting to be held this December and other CSCE 
activities such as cooperation with the United Nations and the 
European Union. 

</TEXT>

