<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bulgarian Minority in Serbia Discussed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bulgarian Minority in Serbia Discussed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1506195794 Sofia BTA in English 1635 GMT 15 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1506195794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, June 15 (BTA) -- Stressing once more 
Bulgaria's position of noninterference in the Yugo-conflict in 
any form whatsoever, Georgi Dimitrov, leader of the Bulgarian 
delegation to the 27th regular meeting of the Committee of 
Senior Officials of the Conference on Security and Cooperation 
in Europe in Prague, stated that Bulgaria was the most badly hit 
by the embargo on the former Yugoslavia, BTA learned from the 
Foreign Ministry spokesman. 
  Referring to the decisions of the CSCE Council of Foreign 
Ministers' meeting in Rome on "continuous control of the 
observance of CSCE standards and principles for human rights 
improvement and protection of minorities in Yugoslavia (Serbia 
and Montenegro)," Mr. Dimitrov praised the results achieved by 
the meeting of representatives of the Bulgarian minority in 
eastern Serbia and officials of the embassies of the CSCE 
participating countries held at the Italian Embassy in Belgrade 
in May. The leader of the Bulgarian delegation insisted on 
ensuring the conditions which would enable the Bulgarian 
minority in Serbia exercise their legitimate rights and freedoms 
in full in compliance with the CSCE standards. 

</TEXT>

