<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   MKDH Leader Views Bilingual Road Sign Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MKDH Leader Views Bilingual Road Sign Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1606105794 Prague CTK in English 1739 GMT 15 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1606105794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, June 15 (CTK) -- Bilingual road signs 
in towns and villages inhabited by ethnic minority populations 
are part of the European standard which should be reached by 
Slovakia before the autumn elections, Pal Farkas, deputy 
chairman of the Hungarian Christian Democratic Movement (MKDH), 
today told CTK. "If a new government bill on place names, to be 
submitted on Friday [17 June], is acceptable for us and the 
coalition I see no reason why it should not be discussed at the 
next parliamentary session," he said. 
  He admitted that he told the Coalition Council today that 
the 
government should not necessarily be supported by Hungarian 
deputies who secure its majority in parliament. "It was 
necessary to recall that our agreement with the coalition as 
well as the recommendations by the Council of Europe are in 
effect. According to the agreement we support the government 
provided it solves this problem also. If the coalition is 
unwilling to do so nobody can expect blind support from us," he 
said. "We are flexible to a certain extent. If a new bill 
allows for a referendum to decide on bilingual road signs then 
we would be able to back it," Farkas said. 
  He said that aggravation of the problems surrounding the 
place names law can indisputably be ascribed to the election 
campaign in which the national feelings of voters are exploited, 
he said. "For us, however, it is a question of our identity. 
We live here, and have our own language so why should not we 
name our villages and towns in our native language as it is 
generally accepted everywhere in Europe," Farkas said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

