<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials Hold Talks at Crans Montana Forum </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Officials Hold Talks at Crans Montana Forum </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Klaus on Talks With Delegations </H4>

<F P=102> LD1906112994 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1000 
GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1906112994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Czech </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] The Universal Economic Forum ends in Crans 
Montana in Switzerland today. In addition to plenary sessions 
and discussions within sections, bilateral talks also played an 
important role. Our special correspondent Lucie Weissova tells 
us about those in which the Czech delegation was involved. 
  [Weissova] [Czech] Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus held talks 
with the host Swiss delegation, from whom he received an 
invitation to pay an official visit to Switzerland. He also 
talked to representatives of the smaller states of the former 
Soviet Union: Moldova, Georgia, Armenia, and Belarus. He told 
us the following about the contents of those talks: 
  [Begin Klaus recording] What I consider significant is that 
these countries explicitly see the model being effected by the 
Czech Republic as being the model for them to follow. We have 
even firmly agreed that for both Moldova and Georgia we might be 
prepared to send a certain delegation of our experts, who would 
advise them as to the logic of the whole transformation process. 
[end recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

