<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Moravcik on Privatization Process </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prime Minister Moravcik on Privatization Process </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1706200494 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1600 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1706200494 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1600 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Regular" interview with Prime Minister Jozef Moravcik by </F>
correspondent Martin Bartisek; place and date not 
given--recorded] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] [Bartisek] A new entity has 
emerged on our political scene--the New Slovakia movement. 
Honorary Chairman Rudolf Mosny has proposed the abolition of 
the Ministry for Administration and Privatization of National 
Property. What do you think about his proposal? It is possible 
to assume, to a certain degree, that it was put forward by a man 
of some experience. Moreover, he says that, in our country, 
privatization has become a political instrument. I am, in fact, 
asking two questions. 
  [Moravcik] I agree with both of them. As far as turning 
privatization into a political issue is concerned, we spoke out 
about this already some time ago, and we are striving to 
depoliticize privatization. From this viewpoint, it is possible 
to agree with this idea. However, as far as the activities of 
our Cabinet are concerned, we strive to respect the above 
principle strictly--that is, we would not like privatization to 
be an arena of political influence by individual parties, to be 
carried out so that supporters of one or the other party gain 
some unfair advantages. This will have a very negative impact. 
If privatization is being linked to policy, it should be only 
economic policy. This is our aim. This means that privatization 
should support the Cabinet's economic policy. 
  The measure we adopted today is aimed at this--we proposed 
releasing 3.5 billion korunas of the money we gained or are 
going to gain through privatization of national property. We 
want to release this money to give an impetus to the development 
of our economy. 
  [Bartisek] However, your reaction to the call for the 
abolition of the Ministry for Privatization was positive. 
  [Moravcik] At present, there are still reasons for the 
existence of the ministry, given the current concept of 
privatization as outlined in the Privatization Act. If we 
change this concept, which is defined by the current norms, we 
might even imagine abolishing the Ministry for Privatization. 
It is, of course, possible to discuss this issue. However, the 
implementation of this idea before the elections can be 
excluded. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

