<H3> <TI>   Redman Discusses Talks With Bosnian Leaders </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Redman Discusses Talks With Bosnian Leaders </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1806205994 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 2000 GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1806205994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Passages contained within quotation marks are recorded; </F>
Redman speaks in English with superimposed Serbo-Croatian 
translation] 
  [Text] Special U.S. envoy Charles Redman held talks with 
Alija Izetbegovic, president of the Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Presidency; Presidency member Ejup Ganic; and Prime Minister 
Haris Silajdzic at the Bosnia-Herzegovina Presidency in Sarajevo 
today. Nedzad Leko reports: 
  [Leko] After three-hour-long talks, only Charles Redman 
addressed the journalists, and said the following: 
  [Redman] "I took advantage of my visit to continue our 
consultations on a number of issues facing Bosnia today -- both 
political and economic -- and the reconstruction of Sarajevo and 
other parts of the country. This evening I am going to Zagreb 
where I will have a meeting with Mr. Akashi, President Tudjman, 
and members of the Croatian Government. I will spend several 
more days in Europe to continue consultations because we all 
believe that this is an important moment to continue working 
toward a more stable, and, we hope, lasting peace. The 
negotiations are very difficult, but we are working hard, and 
will continue to do that. You will probably see me here in 
Sarajevo again soon." 
  [Leko] Asked whether the maps on which the contact group 
worked over the past two days in London were discussed at the 
meeting, Charles Redman said: 
  [Redman] "I am not here in that capacity. These issues are 
obviously always very interesting and important. However, I am 
here for bilateral U.S.-Bosnian relations [as heard], and not in 
the context of the contact group." 

</TEXT>

