<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   VMRO-DPMNE Presses for Border Protection </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    VMRO-DPMNE Presses for Border Protection </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1706135794 Skopje NOVA MAKEDONIJA in Macedonian 17 Jun 94 
p 4 </F>

<F P=103> AU1706135794 </F>
<F P=104>  Skopje NOVA MAKEDONIJA </F>
<F P=105>  Macedonian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The VMRO-DPMNE [Internal Macedonian Revolutionary 
Organization-Democratic Movement for Macedonian National Unity] 
considers that the threats to the security, autonomy, and 
independence of the Republic of Macedonia [The Former Yugoslav 
Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM] from the frequent border 
incidents and activities of Serbian forces on the border with 
Macedonia represent a serious problem, and that the urgent 
protection of the sovereignty of the Macedonian state is 
required, in conformity with the basic postulates defined by 
international law and international agreements. 
  The pro-Serbian leftist government coalition, which fully 
controls the Macedonian Assembly, has not yet proposed any legal 
measures to define and support Macedonia's state border with 
Serbia, as well as with other states, and thus respond to these 
activities of our northern neighbor. Because of all this, the 
northern state border is still being treated as an 
administrative border. 
  The VMRO-DPMNE considers that the government of Branko 
Crvenkovski and Macedonian President Kiro Gligorov are most 
responsible for not resolving this situation, because so far 
they have not done anything to contribute to adapting the 
Macedonian legislation to international law on state sovereignty 
and the protection of territorial integrity. According to 
VMRO-DPMNE, there can be no justification for this leftist 
ruling coalition, which has not yet passed a new law on the 
control of the state borders, on protecting the inviolability of 
the entire length of the borders and thus defining a way for 
solving border violations and incidents, which are occuring 
increasingly frequently. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

