<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tudjman, Redman Discuss Bosnia Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tudjman, Redman Discuss Bosnia Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1806203694 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
2000 GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1806203694 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Franjo Tudjman, president of the Republic of 
Croatia, held talks with Charles Redman, the U.S. President's 
special envoy for the former Yugoslavia, and U.S. Ambassador to 
Croatia Peter Galbraith in the Presidential Palace in Zagreb 
this evening. 
  They exchanged opinions on the political and economic 
situation in Croatia and the peace process in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. Asked if they had discussed the territorial 
division of Bosnia-Herzegovina, whereby the Croat-Bosniak 
Federation would be given 51 percent of Bosnia-Herzegovina and 
the Bosnian Serbs 49 percent, the Croatian president said that 
is the only reasonable solution. 
  Redman said that they had discussed the division only in 
general terms, while President Tudjman was informed about what 
is being attempted by the contact group and with ministers [as 
heard]. We are not at the stage where we can propose anything, 
Redman stressed, but we are working hard at it. 

</TEXT>

