<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO Commander on `Very Valuable' Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NATO Commander on `Very Valuable' Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1706133494 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1000 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1706133494 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1000 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] General Marinus Wilmink, commander of Allied NATO 
Land Forces in Central Europe, ended his four-day official visit 
to Slovakia with talks in the Defense Ministry in Bratislava. 
He also met with journalists at a brief news conference. 
Bernard Roztecky has the details: 
  [Roztecky] After his talks with Andrej Sabol, state 
secretary 
in the Slovak Defense Ministry, Gen. Marinus Wilmink assessed 
his first official visit to Slovakia as very valuable. He 
appreciated the mutual understanding as well as the sharing of 
views on some military issues. He pointed out that future 
cooperation will benefit from such trust. 
  According to General Julius Humaj, Slovak Army commander in 
chief, who was present at the concluding talks, cooperation will 
take place in three main areas: the development of new 
organizational structures in our Army--that is, a transition to 
the system of army corps and brigades similar to that of NATO. 
The other areas cover the introduction of logistics systems in 
army units and simulated training and other training for battle, 
areas in which NATO has rich experience. 
  State Secretary Andrej Sabol also assessed the political 
aspect of the talks, especially in relation to our participation 
in the Partnership for Peace program. He recalled that our 
initiative to set up a NATO consultation center in Bratislava 
met with Gen. Wilmink's understanding. The general appreciated 
the need for more intensive sharing of experience. 
  The commander of NATO land forces in Central Europe will 
leave for NATO headquarters in Germany this afternoon. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

