<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Reports Muslim Attack on British Observers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Reports Muslim Attack on British Observers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1906164794 Paris AFP in English 1615 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1906164794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Sarajevo, June 19 (AFP) -- Troops of Bosnia's 
mainly Moslem army fired on a British UN observation post in 
Gorazde, the United Nations said Sunday [19 June] as it reported 
a growing number of ceasefire violations. Most of the clashes 
are between the Bosnian army and Serb secessionist forces, and 
northeastern Bosnia has seen the biggest increase in military 
activity over the past three days, UN spokesman Eric Chaperon 
said. 
  However, on Saturday [18 June] night Bosnian army forces 
opened fire on a British UN observation post in the eastern 
enclave of Gorazde, Chaperon said. The British force fired 
back, he added without saying if there were casualties. At dawn 
Sunday Bosnian Moslem and Serb forces also clashed in Gorazde, 
he added. [passage omitted] 
  Chaperon said the head of UN forces in Bosnia, General Sir 
Michael Rose of Britain, sent a letter Saturday to the 
commanders of the Bosnian army and Serb forces asking for strict 
observance of the ceasefire. Rose cited incidents in which one 
or the other side had broken the truce. [passage omitted] 
  Chaperon also reported that a Danish UN medical team, due to 
travel from Sarajevo to Gorazde, has been stuck in between for 
five days at the Serb-held town of Rogatica after refusing to 
submit to Serb searches of their equipment. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

