<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   SLD Estimates Tenfold Increase in Councillors </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SLD Estimates Tenfold Increase in Councillors </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2006171294 Warsaw PAP in Polish 1450 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2006171294 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Warsaw, 20 Jun--During a news conference on 20 
June, Jerzy Szmajdzinski, general secretary of the Social 
Democracy of the Polish Republic, said that, according to 
Democratic Left Alliance [SLD] estimates, the number of local 
councillors from that party increased tenfold after the 19 June 
local elections. There were 758 councillors during the previous 
term. The SLD won the largest number of seats (over 50 percent) 
in Wloclawek, Sosnowiec, and Czeladz. [passage omitted] 
  Szmajdzinski said that, in 29 towns where proportional 
elections took place, the SLD won 30 percent of the seats, which 
was comparable with the parliamentary election results. The SLD 
won 40-50 percent of seats in 10 cities, including Lodz, Zielona 
Gora, Bydgoszcz, Dabrowa Gornicza, Grudziadz, and Lublin. 

</TEXT>

