<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Heavy Fighting Between Muslim Forces Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Heavy Fighting Between Muslim Forces Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2006162394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1559 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2006162394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Petrovac, June (TANJUG)--Heavy fighting between 
forces loyal to Bosnia's Moslem fundamentalist leader Alija 
Izetbegovic and those of the Autonomous Province of Western 
Bosnia (APZB) continued Monday in the Moslem enclave of Cazin 
Krajina in Western Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  The radio station in Velika Kladusa, the APZB centre, said 
Izetbegovic's forces had attempted to infiltrate a terrorist 
group and had opened artillery and small arms fire on APZB 
troops. 
  Bihac radio, controlled by Izetbegovic's forces, said the 
forces of the Sarajevo Moslem government firmly controlled all 
their positions despite continuing attacks by the APZB army. 
  APZB leader Fikret Abdic is opposed to Izetbegovic's policy 
of war and wants Moslems, Serbs and Croats to live peacefully 
side by side. Immediately after the proclamation of the APZB in 
autumn last year, Izetbegovic's troops attacked the forces and 
population of the new autonomy. The conflicts, which have so 
far claimed hundreds of lives, did not stop after the latest 
Bosnia ceasefire came into effect on June 10. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

