<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yugoslav Army Said To Occupy Border Areas </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yugoslav Army Said To Occupy Border Areas </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2006174794 Skopje NOVA MAKEDONIJA in Macedonian 16 Jun 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> AU2006174794 </F>
<F P=104>  Skopje NOVA MAKEDONIJA </F>
<F P=105>  Macedonian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Strategic Point at Straza Seized"] </F>
  [Text] Yesterday a team of NOVA MAKEDONIJA journalists went 
near a zone that has been occupied by members of the regular 
Yugoslav Army, 250 meters into Macedonian [The Former Yugoslav 
Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM] territory. They also control a 
strategic point on Mount Straza near Kriva Palanka, including 50 
additional meters of territory, and therefore there is all 
together 300 meters of territory under their control. 
Macedonian Army patrols are being turned away from this area 
with the following words: "Do not approach -- this is Serbia." 
Members of the U.S. UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] also took 
up their positions yesterday. However, it is evident that the 
Serbian Army does not have any intention of withdrawing. 
  For the chief of the Yugoslav Army General Staff, Momcilo 
Perisic, the events on the Macedonian-Serbian border are nothing 
but a media lie. Moreover, Perisic stated that Macedonia 
accepted the UN forces, within which the Americans are the most 
numerous, not for the sake of protecting the Macedonian people, 
but for the sake of forming their own base. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

