<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozloduy Plant Operating at `Reduced Capacity' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozloduy Plant Operating at `Reduced Capacity' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2006095794 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 0900 
GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2006095794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Bulgarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Veselin Angelov from Kozloduy] </F>
  [Text] [Announcer] After speedily completed repairs, the 
No. 1 Reactor Unit at the Kozloduy Nuclear Power Plant was put 
back into service. But, as our correspondent Veselin Angelov 
reports, the nuclear plant is operating at reduced capacity at 
the moment. 
  [Angelov] The reduced operating capacity was made necessary 
by the fall in electricity consumption throughout the country. 
In fact, only three of the six generating units are in 
operation at Kozloduy at the moment: These are Units No. 1 and 
No. 2, each producing 420 megawatts, and the 1,000-megawatt No. 
6 Unit. The remaining reactors are shut down for planned 
maintenance or for reloading with fresh nuclear fuel. The 
period of their shutdown is being utilized to introduce some new 
technical features, connected with improving safety of 
operation. This is a continuous process, prompted by the 
constant improvements in international standards and the 
requirements of the World Association of Nuclear Operators. 

</TEXT>

